# Go Project Structure — Logic & Rationale

## cmd/ — Entry Points

**What:** One directory per executable. `cmd/api/main.go`, `cmd/worker/main.go`.

**Why:** Go compiles to single binaries. Each `main` package produces one binary. Separating entry points keeps build targets clear.

**Logic in main:** Minimal. Parse config, create dependencies (DB, repo, service), wire router, start server. No business logic — delegate to internal packages.

## internal/ — Private Code

**What:** Code that cannot be imported by other modules. Enforced by Go compiler.

**Why:** Encapsulation. Your module's API is what you export from the root or `pkg/`. `internal/` is implementation detail — other projects cannot depend on it, reducing coupling.

**Substructure:**
- `domain/` — entities, value objects, repository interfaces. No external deps.
- `application/` — commands, queries, services. Depends on domain.
- `infrastructure/` — HTTP handlers, DB implementations, Redis, etc. Depends on domain (implements interfaces).

## pkg/ — Public Reusable Code

**What:** Code intended for import by other projects. Optional.

**Why:** If you build a library others will use, put it in `pkg/`. If the project is an application only, you may not need `pkg/`.

**Naming:** `pkg/` or root-level exported packages. `internal/` is never importable.

## Import Conventions

**Order:** stdlib → blank line → third-party → blank line → local (module path).

**Why:** Readability. Grouping makes dependencies obvious. `goimports` enforces this.

**Module path:** Use full path `github.com/org/project/internal/domain`. Avoid relative imports across packages — they break when packages move.

## Testing

**Same package:** `foo_test.go` in package `foo` — white-box testing, can access unexported symbols. Use `package foo_test` for black-box.

**Table-driven:** Slice of structs with input/want; loop with `t.Run(name, fn)`. Reduces duplication, easy to add cases.

**t.Run subtests:** Each case runs as subtest. `go test -run TestFoo/bar` runs one case. Parallel: `t.Parallel()` — be careful with shared state.

**Integration tests:** `*_integration_test.go` or `test/integration/`. Use build tag `//go:build integration` so they don't run in CI by default.
